relative="1" as="geometry"> <mxPoint as="offset" /> </mxGeometry> </mxCell> <mxCell id="2prFuzN1p3rCyXP5tDg9-30" value="Why the Factory Pattern is Ideal:
Variety of Appointment Types:


You have different types of appointments: consultation call, face-to-face consultation, online conversation, and check-up. The Factory Pattern is perfect for creating instances of these different types without tightly coupling the client code to the specific classes.
Scalability:


As you expand the system to include more appointment types or change existing ones, the Factory Pattern provides a centralized place to manage the creation logic, making it easier to maintain and extend.
Separation of Concerns:


By using the Factory Pattern, you separate the creation logic from the scheduling logic, which makes the code cleaner and more modular." style="text;whiteSpace=wrap;fontFamily=Times New Roman;" div.div:
This behavioral design pattern is the best choice because it lets you define a mechanism to notify multiple objects about any events that happen to the object theyre observing and in our case for vaccine list : it ensures that each user has access to their complete
vaccination history within the system(early and prime immunizations), and also is responsible for notifying observers (users) when there are updates to the vaccination record.
